Here are both approaches:

**1. Register the route in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public AppShell()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
}
```

**2. Navigate from `ProductListPage` — two approaches:**

```csharp
// Approach A: Pass product ID as a query string
async void OnProductTapped(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");
}

// Approach B: Pass the full Product object
async void OnProductTapped(Product product)
{
    var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
}
```

**3. Receive both in the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public string ProductId
    {
        get => _productId;
        set => SetProperty(ref _productId, value);
    }

    public Product Product
    {
        get => _product;
        set => SetProperty(ref _product, value);
    }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: string parameter arrives as object — call ToString()
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service using the ID...
        }

        // Approach B: complex object arrives as its original type — cast it
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            Product = product;
            ProductId = product.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | Query string (`?productId=...`) | `ShellNavigationQueryParameters` |
|---|---|---|
| Data type | String only | Any object |
| Serialization | You build the URI | No serialization needed |
| Use case | Simple IDs, small values | Full model objects |
| Back-nav / deep link friendly | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (object is transient) |

Both approaches call the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` method, so your ViewModel can handle either or both in one place. Always `await` the `GoToAsync` call to avoid race conditions.
